Basic Set Up

Set the Working Directory

  • SUPER IMPORTANT STEP: You need this to locate files youll be importing
  • getwd(): prints the working directory
  • setwd(): setting the working directory manually
  • Your working directory should contain all your data files!!!

Importing the Data

  • For our purposes, we are importing a TXT file
  • REDCap offers imports using the CSV format (use the read.csv command)

  • R supports both, along with multiple other formats (packages can help load Excel files)

  • names: column names
  • nrow: number of rows

  • ncol: number of columns

Data Manipulation

Filtering Data

Here, we're selecting the weights of current smokers and storing it in an object called tobacco_users_weights. We're also selecting the weights of non-smokers and storing it in non_tobacco_users_weights.

  • %>% is a way to send the data down to the next command. Instead of saying data_nhanes <- filter(data_nhanes, Marijuana=="Yes") followed by data_nhanes <- select(data_nhanes, Yes)
  • filter: selects rows based on certain criteria. Here were selecting who indicated Yes under the SmokeNow variable
  • select: this selects specific columns. Here, were selecting the Weight column

Without Piping:

tobacco_users_weights <- filter(data_nhanes, SmokeNow=="Yes") 
tobacco_users_weights <- select(tobacco_users_weights, Weight) 
tobacco_users_weights <- unlist(tobacco_users_weights)


non_tobacco_users_weights <- filter(data_nhanes, SmokeNow=="No") 
non_tobacco_users_weights <- select(non_tobacco_users_weights, Weight) 
non_tobacco_users_weights <- unlist(non_tobacco_users_weights)

With Piping:

tobacco_users_weights <- data_nhanes %>% filter(SmokeNow=="Yes") %>% select(Weight) %>% unlist
non_tobacco_users_weights <- data_nhanes %>% filter(SmokeNow=="No") %>% select(Weight) %>% unlist

Creating a New Variable

What if we want to calculate everyone's age in years, using the AgeMonths variable and create a new variable called AgeYears? We can do this using the mutate function.

data_nhanes <- data_nhanes %>% mutate(AgeYears = AgeMonths/12)
summary(data_nhanes$AgeYears)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    0.00   16.58   34.83   35.01   52.00   79.92    5038

Continuous Outcomes: t-Test

We can use a t-test to compare two continuous outcomes between two groups.

Let's first visualize these using a boxplot:

boxplot(tobacco_users_weights, non_tobacco_users_weights)

Then we'll use a statistical test:

t.test(tobacco_users_weights, non_tobacco_users_weights)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  tobacco_users_weights and non_tobacco_users_weights
## t = -5.5235, df = 3138.1, p-value = 3.595e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -5.374468 -2.558447
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  80.53505  84.50151

Linear Models:

What if we want to see the effect multiple variables have on an outcome? We can use a linear model:

In this example, we'll look at the effects of age and weight on income:

model = lm(HHIncomeMid ~ Age + Weight, data = data_nhanes)
